<subSubSection id="A3CDDCDD7B72BF428823A4396D372667" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="78E9F7C78548A46D644515EDBB027183" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">Material examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9D76D28D22EFB2713223650090C26ED6" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">
CAMBODIA (all coll. RBINS): 4 males, Siem Reap prov., Angkhor, Preah Khan Temple, 24 
<normalizedToken id="63929ED409B07EC86AE540B75215DC1B" originalValue="January–">January-</normalizedToken>
21 February 2006, Malaise trap in secondary forest (leg. Oul Yothin); 1 male, Siem Reap prov., Angkhor, Preah Khan Temple, 12 May 2006, sweep netting (leg. Oul Yothin).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C2F808EAEB4B6AD9D6FF63A2EF04F027" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">
THAILAND: 1 male (coll. RBINS); Loei prov., Na Haeo Field Research Station (
<geoCoordinate id="C79427BD5A2978761D7F120C13AEB1F4" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="1" value="17.490862">17°29'27.1&quot;N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="D0BA0FC4AAADBBFF7B6803F8DF7E38D1" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="1" value="101.059616">101°03'34.6&quot;E</geoCoordinate>
), 769 m, 16 May 2003, sweep netting along stream and water fall in secondary forest (leg. P Grootaert).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E2AF8D6F7F896DB19F9E019823B7D715" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="EE687420BC63988195654AD84B4532B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="73744F7685852611C34D36E3BD3EBFA9" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">Costa swollen before and at the level where R1 joins the costa (Figure 4). Wing clear. Hind coxa yellow. Tip of phallus ventrally with a number of denticles. Hypandrium unarmed. Cercus (Figure 5) with weakly digitated margin. Marginal bristles on cercus brown. Apical marginal bristle longest, blunt-tipped inserted on a long tubercle; subsequent two marginals flattened and blunt-tipped, subsequent bristles with simple tip; 6th bristle fine, pale; subsequent bristles long, brown. A long blunt-tipped interior, longer than the apical marginal.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="63D73635E5FD5E121F6A9D931B3827EA" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" type="description">
<paragraph id="7836777F202658EE5447B94E28727C75" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FFC9A7D1D9AE26766088B16EDD92FE74" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">
We refer to the detailed description of 
<taxonomicName id="E1E025278D5639F59485DC5B36B6F668" genus="L." lsidName="L. dentalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" rank="species" species="dentalis">L. dentalis</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="274B67DD07BEC567A67654E0313673DE" author="Zhang, L" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" pagination="197 - 203" title="Species of Lichtwardtia from China (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3157/061.135.0208" volume="135" year="2009">Zhang et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DB3736FE9A53FF2830AAA0105693730B" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" type="comments">
<paragraph id="C3ADF98738ED90FD0DD6ECEAA80AF4D9" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7AA98ADB03000C45C58AE169AA019B8E" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">
The specimens from northern Thailand and central Cambodia correspond entirely to the description and figures given by 
<bibRefCitation id="9B1748ADDEF8453CDCD5CB0099FD4BA7" author="Zhang, L" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" pagination="197 - 203" title="Species of Lichtwardtia from China (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3157/061.135.0208" volume="135" year="2009">Zhang et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. Especially the widening of the costa where the R1 joins the costa as is drawn by 
<bibRefCitation id="1275B43A1E1A8E32080981CD92CD9621" author="Zhang, L" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" pagination="197 - 203" title="Species of Lichtwardtia from China (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3157/061.135.0208" volume="135" year="2009">Zhang et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
but not mentioned in the description. The new records are not unlikely since the locality in the Loei province (Thailand) and the one in Cambodia are not so far from the southern Yunnan province (China) that is the type locality of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="54F623B0273561178B7CBC6C4BF279A0" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicName id="1D22D4B76107D87D94534576CD54FB76" genus="L." lsidName="L. dentalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" rank="species" species="dentalis">L. dentalis</taxonomicName>
is very closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="FF4732DFAE2D0C08235A019D40D55F71" genus="L." lsidName="L. semakau" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" rank="species" species="semakau">L. semakau</taxonomicName>
sp. n. from Singapore and we refer to the comments under the latter species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
